The trial was since paused due to investigations into the risk of blood clotting vs. the reward of immunity in his age group. We will encourage vaccination in future once the trial is successfully completed.
vaccinelikelywhyparent: I have already had a first dose. I consider the benefit of vaccination greatly to outweigh the risks for people of my age.
vaccinewhynotchild: They were offered a trial vaccine but declined after considering the risks and the down side of potentially being ill the next day, which was an important school day for them. They would certainly reconsider in future. There is no widely available vaccine for children his age in the UK at the moment, so it's an academic question right now.
specifypositive: Home schooling with parents increased our understanding of how he learns and what he struggles with, and left us better placed to help outside school hours. He enjoyed some of the different kinds of activity we did during home schooling and took up some new hobbies which he greatly enjoys.
covidprecautionswhy: I consider most of these measures vital for slowing the spread of infection and therefore bringing health benefits for our community. There has been a recent increase in what is permitted as 'COVID-safe', and we've taken some advantage of the freedom to meet others outdoors for the social benefits.
challenges: No real technical challenges, but the hardest thing has been prolonged separation from grandparents and (until schools recently reopened) a lack of face to face time with friends and peers.
benefits: It has encouraged us to be creative in looking for sources of learning materials, to dig deeper into areas of passion our son would not have had time to explore at school, and practise new skills and technology connecting people remotely. I have also had some extra employment to advise and help others with this.
anything_else: The biggest impact at school may be the overall challenge to address a gap which has opened up between those who had good technology and support during school closure and those who did not. I'm slightly concerned that my son might not get all the resources at school that he would otherwise have had, but I'm much more concerned that the work ahead to close this gap might end up creating or deepening social divisions within classes.

vaccinelikelywhychild: I chose this answer for several reasons. The vaccine isn't approved, it's simply authorized for emergency use. A RNA vaccine's effects on the human body especially long term are unknown. The trials are incomplete on humans and animals, the risks of side effects are much greater to me than the risk of COVID-19. And honestly I feel it's scientific experiment that we have zero interest in being a part of. In my world, COVID-19 has not proven to be as detrimental as it's portrayed on the news.

vaccinewhynotparent: There is no plausible reason for a vaccination against a virus that has not been isolated for identification and the virus isn't even in the vaccine, so it's unacceptable to me to Have something unapproved only authorized for emergency use injected into my body because there are an incredible amount of unknowns. The virus mutates, and so far the vaccine isn't proving effective as many who have been vaccinated still test positive for Covid.
